  <entry>
    <id>tag:www.gov.uk,2005:NewsArticle/17230</id>
    <published>2012-11-30T00:15:00+00:00</published>
    <updated>2012-11-30T00:15:00+00:00</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/think-don-t-drink-drive-this-christmas"/>
    <title>THINK! Don’t drink drive this Christmas</title>
    <content type="html">&lt;div class="govspeak"&gt;&lt;p&gt;THINK! and the Association of Chief Police Officers (&lt;abbr title="Association of Chief Police Officers"&gt;ACPO&lt;/abbr&gt;) are joining forces to warn drivers that getting behind the wheel after a festive tipple could see them end up behind bars this Christmas.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A hard-hitting television advert highlighting the consequences of drink driving will be shown throughout December as part of the Department for Transport’s THINK! Christmas drink drive campaign. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Association of Chief Police Officers"&gt;ACPO&lt;/abbr&gt; today also launched its anti-drink and drug driving enforcement campaign, warning that young drivers and people driving the morning after a night of drinking pose a huge risk.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Road Safety Minister Stephen Hammond said:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Drivers should be in no doubt that if they get behind the wheel after drinking this Christmas, they risk losing their licence as well as facing a fine and even a prison sentence.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Christmas should be a time for a celebration not a night in the cells. That is why our TV advert reminds drivers of the consequences of a drink drive conviction.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;In 2011, 280 people were killed in accidents where the driver was over the limit. Our message is clear: Do not let a selfish decision ruin your life or someone else’s.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Association of Chief Police Officers"&gt;ACPO&lt;/abbr&gt; roads policing lead, Deputy Chief Constable Suzette Davenport, said: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;If you don’t drink and drive this Christmas you reduce the risk of killing an innocent person, or yourself. It is really that simple.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;It is an absolute scourge on our society and shameful that in 2012 some drivers fail to realise the impact of drink or drug driving. Next year’s figures could include them or one of their family members.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Last year, drivers aged between 20 and 24 failed more breath tests than any other age group. This year’s THINK! Christmas drink drive campaign is aimed at young people who are shown to be consistently over-represented in drink drive casualty figures.* &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Association of Chief Police Officers"&gt;ACPO&lt;/abbr&gt;’s enforcement campaign targets well-intentioned drivers who do not think they are breaking the law but may be over the legal limit by the time they get into their cars in the morning. Police forces will be taking to roads across the country to stop and check drivers. Those found to be over the limit will face prosecution, which can lead to a jail sentence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;DCC Davenport added: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;There are some drivers who think they are obeying the law but are in fact breaking it by getting into their cars the morning after a night of drinking.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;People may be surprised to hear that last year between the hours of 6am and 11am more than 400 people failed breath tests (or refused to provide a specimen), which is more than those caught for the hour before or after midnight. **&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Drivers need to be aware that regardless of the time of day they are caught, whether they are going to work or taking children to school, they will face the same penalties as someone who has chosen to drink heavily in a pub and driven at night.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Robert Gifford, Executive Director of the Parliamentary Advisory Council for Transport Safety (PACTS), said: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;It is good to see the department re-launching the Christmas drink-drive campaign. This advert reminds drivers that the choice is theirs but the responsibility for the wrong choice will stay with them for years to come. If in doubt, do not try to mix two activities. Stay sober at Christmas and during the rest of the year.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As well as the THINK! campaign, the Department for Transport is currently consulting on a package of tough measures to crack down on drink drivers. This includes removing drink drivers’ rights to demand a blood or urine test. This is because evidence shows it is used as a delaying tactic by drivers caught over the limit. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="note-to-editors"&gt;Note to editors&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It is provisionally estimated that 2011 saw 280 deaths, 1290 serious injuries and 9,990 total casualties directly related to drink driving incidents&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;The THINK! Christmas Drink Drive campaign budget totals £783,925 &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;The THINK! TV advert - Moment of Doubt - will be aired 4 December to 23 December. For a high-resolution copy of the advert contact the Department for Transport’s press office on 020 7944 6898&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;THINK! campaign posters can be downloaded directly from the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://think.direct.gov.uk/drink-driving.html"&gt;campaign site&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Association of Chief Police Officers"&gt;ACPO&lt;/abbr&gt;’s Christmas campaign runs from 1 December 2012 to 1 January 2013 &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;For more information about the Department for Transport’s consultation into the removal of a driver’s right to a blood test, read this &lt;a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/tough-new-measures-to-tackle-drink-drivers"&gt;recent press release&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;*&lt;a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/ras51-reported-drinking-and-driving"&gt;View the table showing drink drivers by age - article RAS51004&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;**&lt;a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/ras51-reported-drinking-and-driving"&gt;View the table showing numbers of failed breath tests - article RAS51003&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;p&gt;Press enquiries: 020 7944 3066&lt;br&gt;
Out of hours: 020 7944 4292&lt;br&gt;
Public enquiries: 0300 330 3000  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:www.gov.uk,2005:DetailedGuide/17204</id>
    <published>2012-11-29T22:48:47+00:00</published>
    <updated>2012-11-29T22:48:47+00:00</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.gov.uk/importing-live-fish-molluscs-and-crustacea"/>
    <title>Importing and exporting live fish, molluscs and crustacea</title>
    <content type="html">&lt;div class="govspeak"&gt;&lt;h2 id="introduction"&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before you can import live fish, molluscs and/or crustacea into the UK, you must be authorised as an aquaculture production business by the Fish Health Inspectorate (&lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All consignments of fish, molluscs and/or crustacea from outside the European Union (&lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;) need to be accompanied by a health certificate. This is issued by the competent authority in the country of origin and confirms the health status of the fish, molluscs or crustacea in the consignment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you are importing fish, molluscs and/or crustacea from within the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;, your consignments only need to be accompanied by a health certificate if they include species that are susceptible to, or carriers of, a disease controlled in Great Britain (&lt;abbr title="Great Britain"&gt;GB&lt;/abbr&gt;). In both cases you need to notify the appropriate authority before your imports arrive. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This guide explains the authorisations and documentation you need in order to import live fish, molluscs and/or crustacea. It also gives guidance on what happens if errors occur, and the steps you must take when exporting.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="authorisation-and-documentation-for-live-fish-mollusc-and-crustacea-importers"&gt;Authorisation and documentation for live fish, mollusc and crustacea importers&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Anyone importing live fish, molluscs and crustacea into Great Britain needs to be authorised by the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt;. This includes imports intended for:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;farming&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;relaying&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;‘put and take’ fisheries&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;restocking&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;open and closed ornamental facilities, including pets and purchases for own collection&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;scientific research&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;public aquaria and zoos&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;spas and medical use (nibble fish)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you hold fish, molluscs and/or crustacea on your own site, your application to be authorised may need to include a biosecurity measures plan. For guidance on biosecurity measures plans, you can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Book-Importer-BMP-v2.pdf"&gt;download biosecurity measures guidance for importers from the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF, 453KB)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Authorisation is free of charge and you can apply using form AAH2. You can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-AAH2.pdf"&gt;download &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; form AAH2 from the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF, 51KB)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="importing-live-fish-mollusc-and-crustacea-from-outside-the-eu"&gt;Importing live fish, mollusc and crustacea from outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Countries that are not in the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; or a member of the European Free Trade Association (&lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt;) are treated as ‘third countries’ for import purposes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Imports of fish, molluscs and/or crustacea from third countries must be accompanied by a health certificate issued by the competent authority in the country of origin. The authority must follow model documents issued by the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and will often charge for the service.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-Coldwater-Cert-13.11.12.pdf" title="Open Health Certificates"&gt;Open certificates&lt;/a&gt; are required for fish, mollusc, crustacean intended for farming, relaying, put and take fisheries, open ornamental facilities and susceptible/ vector species for scientific research or public display.  Stock must originate from a country/ territory permitted by the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;. &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-Tropical-Cert-13.11.12.pdf" title="Closed Health Certificates"&gt;Closed certificates&lt;/a&gt; are required for ornamental fish intended for closed facilities, nibble fish for medical/ spa use and non susceptible/ vector species for scientific research or public display&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;Imports that arrive in Great Britain directly from a third country must go through a border inspection post (&lt;abbr title="border inspection post"&gt;BIP&lt;/abbr&gt;) where the health certificate is inspected by Animal Health (&lt;abbr title="Animal Health"&gt;AH&lt;/abbr&gt;). You will need to inform &lt;abbr title="Animal Health"&gt;AH&lt;/abbr&gt; about your import at least one clear working day in advance using a Common Veterinary Entry Document (&lt;abbr title="Common Veterinary Entry Document"&gt;CVED&lt;/abbr&gt;). You can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-CVED-Notification.pdf"&gt;download a &lt;abbr title="Common Veterinary Entry Document"&gt;CVED&lt;/abbr&gt; notification form from the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF, 67KB)&lt;/a&gt;. For details of the timescales to observe when using a &lt;abbr title="Common Veterinary Entry Document"&gt;CVED&lt;/abbr&gt; and also for contact details of &lt;abbr title="border inspection posts"&gt;BIPs&lt;/abbr&gt; in Great Britain, &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-CVED-Timetable.pdf"&gt;download the &lt;abbr title="Common Veterinary Entry Document"&gt;CVED&lt;/abbr&gt; timetable for notifications of intended imports from the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF, 35KB)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="importing-live-fish-molluscs-and-crustacea-from-within-the-eu"&gt;Importing live fish, molluscs and crustacea from within the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Different rules apply for movements from &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and &lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt; member countries. Health certification is only required if the species being imported is either a vector/carrier of or is susceptible to an &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; controlled disease. You can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/marine/Fish-Shellfish/FHI/importexport/vectorspecies"&gt;read a list of controlled diseases, and vector and susceptible species on the Scottish Government website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You must also notify the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; of all movements of fish, molluscs or crustacea into Great Britain from &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and &lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt; member countries using form AAH1, except tropical species for ornamental use. &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Form-AAH1.pdf"&gt;Download &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; form AAH1 from the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website (PDF, 265KB)&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, although the Isle of Man, Northern Ireland, Jersey and Guernsey are all part of the UK, they are recognised as separate ‘health zones’ to Great Britain. This means that movements from these areas must be accompanied by any necessary health certificates.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="call-to-action"&gt;
&lt;h3 id="fish-and-shellfish-intended-for-human-consumption"&gt;Fish and shellfish intended for human consumption&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you import live or dead fish and shellfish for immediate human consumption or immediate processing for human consumption, your business doesn’t need to be authorised. If your imports are from outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; or consist of fish from another Member State, they will require health and hygiene certification. You can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.food.gov.uk/foodindustry/imports/want_to_import/fisheryproducts/%20"&gt;find out about importing fish and shellfish for human consumption on the Food Standards Agency (&lt;abbr title="Food Standards Agency"&gt;FSA&lt;/abbr&gt;) website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2 id="additional-import-requirements-and-post-import-controls"&gt;Additional import requirements and post import controls&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition to general import requirements, there are other controls that may be required when importing endangered. And there are also post import controls when you introduce species to UK waters, hold non-native species or export them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="endangered-species"&gt;Endangered species&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are some species that are recognised world-wide as being endangered. The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (&lt;abbr title="Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species"&gt;CITES&lt;/abbr&gt;) is an international agreement designed to control the import, export and commercial use of these species. If you want to import any species that are on the &lt;abbr title="Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species"&gt;CITES&lt;/abbr&gt; list you will need a &lt;abbr title="Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species"&gt;CITES&lt;/abbr&gt; permit. You can &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalhealth/CITES/"&gt;find out about &lt;abbr title="Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species"&gt;CITES&lt;/abbr&gt; on the &lt;abbr title="Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs"&gt;Defra&lt;/abbr&gt; website&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="additional-controls"&gt;Additional controls&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Certain species are controlled by additional licensing regimes after their import. These include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;a href="/non-native-fish"&gt;non-native crayfish and lobster deposits&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;a href="/non-native-crayfish-and-lobster-deposits"&gt;non-native fish&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="movement-controls"&gt;Movement controls&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For all introductions of fish into open inland waters in the UK, you must get &lt;a href="/section-30-fish-health-checks"&gt;‘Section 30’ consent&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you are planning on exporting fish from &lt;abbr title="Great Britain"&gt;GB&lt;/abbr&gt;, there are certain steps you need to take. These depend on whether you are exporting to another &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; member state or to a country outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="when-importing-errors-occur"&gt;When importing errors occur&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, a mistake can occur with the legal process of importing live fish, molluscs and/or crustacea into Great Britain. While the consignment is at a border inspection post an error with the consignment or the accompanying documentation may be identified. For example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;some or all of the documentation may become lost in transit&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;errors may occur in the quantity of animals in the consignment&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;errors might happen in the accompanying health certificate&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the health certificate may be incomplete&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="what-is-a-regulation-23"&gt;What is a Regulation 23?&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A ‘Regulation 23’ is the name given to a notice issued under Regulation 23(1) of the Trade in Animals and Related Products Regulations 2011. A Regulation 23 allows animals, including fish, molluscs or crustacea, to enter Great Britain even though there has been an error with the import process. It will be issued to prevent a consignment of animals being destroyed, as long as they can be isolated well enough to pose a low health risk to Great Britain.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="who-is-a-regulation-23-issued-to"&gt;Who is a Regulation 23 issued to?&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A Regulation 23 is served on the importer of the consignment. This is because they are the person who appears to be in charge of the animals at the time of the importation and when the veterinary checks were made. As an importer, it is your responsibility to make sure that all the terms of the Regulation 23 are complied with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="isolation-of-the-consignment"&gt;Isolation of the consignment&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before the Regulation 23 is served, as an importer you will be consulted about where the consignment can be isolated to. This may be a facility run by you or a site operated by a third party.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All isolation sites must have been approved by the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; and must be totally physically separate. They must have separate equipment and procedures, and the stock must remain in the facility until the Regulation 23 has been released.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is your responsibility as the importer to make sure that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;any third parties involved are aware of the terms of Regulation 23&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the animals are isolated to prevent the introduction or spread of disease&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="how-and-when-is-a-regulation-23-released"&gt;How and when is a Regulation 23 released?&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before a Regulation 23 can be released, you must resolve the problem that led to the Regulation 23 being issued.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If there is an error with the health certificate, you must arrange for the certificate to be amended or replaced by the competent authority in the country of origin.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If problems with the documentation can’t be resolved, the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; may sample and test the consignment for disease. This involves the sacrifice of a minimum of 30 animals and a delay of between two and three weeks.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="if-the-species-are-non-susceptible-tropical-species"&gt;If the species are non-susceptible tropical species&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If the species involved aren’t a vector/carrier of or susceptible to a controlled disease, a Regulation 23 won’t be issued for documentation errors. Instead, the consignment will be issued with a Regulation 16 requiring the importer to correct paperwork errors but not requiring the animals to be isolated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="exporting-fish-molluscs-and-crustacea-from-great-britain"&gt;Exporting fish, molluscs and crustacea from Great Britain&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Exports of live fish, molluscs and crustacea from Great Britain often require health certification. The steps you need to take depend on whether you are exporting to other &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and &lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt; member states or to countries outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="exporting-to-eu-and-efta-countries"&gt;Exporting to &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and &lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt; countries&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When you export to &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; and &lt;abbr title="European Free Trade Association"&gt;EFTA&lt;/abbr&gt; member states, your consignments only need to be accompanied by health certificates if the species you are exporting are susceptible to or vectors of &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; controlled diseases. If they are, you will need to get the consignment inspected by the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; before the health certificate is issued. This is carried out free of charge but you do need to provide five working days notice to the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="exporting-to-countries-outside-the-eu"&gt;Exporting to countries outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The requirements for exporting to countries outside the &lt;abbr title="European Union"&gt;EU&lt;/abbr&gt; are set by the competent authority in the country of destination. It is your responsibility as the exporter to find out what the requirements are and to obtain copies of all necessary health certificates, including translations, that must accompany your consignments. You must also clarify who is an acceptable signatory: a qualified veterinarian or fish health specialist, for example. You must provide these certificates to the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; and ensure they are accurate and will be accepted by the destination country’s competent authority.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; will then decide if your aquaculture production business site can meet the requirements. If they decide that it can’t, they will contact you to discuss the matter further and outline the options available. If your site can’t meet the requirements, you may decide to contact the competent authority to ask them to revise their requirements.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If an &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; signature is required, and possible, the &lt;abbr title="Fish Health Inspectorate"&gt;FHI&lt;/abbr&gt; will arrange a visit, as well as discussing charges and issuing with you before they proceed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="further-information"&gt;Further information&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;h3 id="fhi-helpline"&gt;
